<section id="philosophy">
    <h2>The Insulin Model of Obesity</h2>

    <div class="key-point">
        <h3>Core Thesis</h3>
        <blockquote>
            "Type 2 diabetes is a disease of too much insulin, not too little. We've been treating the symptom (high blood sugar) while ignoring the cause (hyperinsulinemia). Fasting is the most powerful tool we have because it's the only thing that directly lowers insulin levels."
        </blockquote>
    </div>

    <h3>Why Calories Don't Work</h3>
    <p>Dr. Fung argues that the "calories in, calories out" model fails because it ignores hormones:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Calorie restriction lowers metabolism:</strong> Your body adapts by burning fewer calories</li>
        <li><strong>Insulin drives fat storage:</strong> High insulin tells your body to store, not burn, fat</li>
        <li><strong>Frequent eating keeps insulin elevated:</strong> 6 small meals = constantly high insulin</li>
        <li><strong>Hunger is hormonal:</strong> You can't willpower your way through hormonal hunger</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>The Fasting Solution</h3>
    <p>Fasting works where calorie restriction fails:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Insulin drops dramatically:</strong> No food = no insulin secretion</li>
        <li><strong>Metabolism stays elevated:</strong> Short-term fasting increases metabolic rate</li>
        <li><strong>Fat burning activates:</strong> Low insulin allows fat cells to release stored energy</li>
        <li><strong>Insulin sensitivity improves:</strong> Cells become responsive to insulin again</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="warning-box">
        <h3>The Two-Compartment Problem</h3>
        <p>Dr. Fung explains that your body has two energy "compartments" - a small glycogen reserve (like a refrigerator) and a large fat reserve (like a freezer). High insulin locks the freezer door. You can't access your fat stores while insulin is high, so you stay hungry even while carrying excess body fat.</p>
    </div>

